summary: Not all weight loss is good weight loss. Period. I recognize that our society is messed up and values thinness above genuine...
body: Not all weight loss is good weight loss. Period. I recognize that our society is messed up and values thinness above genuine health but I’m honestly very tired of having to correct people when they congratulate me on my weight loss. I thought I was going to die for half a year, thought my body was straight up rejecting life. I’ve struggled with body image my whole life and I can confidently say skinny isn’t my ideal, I’ve never felt weaker or more disconnected from my body. Being skinny will always remind me of being scared and sick. I want to be strong, happy, and healthy this year and for the first time in my life that means gaining weight to achieve my goals. Health>bullshit beauty standards.

summary: Why am I terrible at running on some days, and great on others? via /r/Fitness
title: Why am I terrible at running on some days, and great on others? via /r/Fitness
body:
I mean some days I just hit a wall at only just over a km and my mind is going crazy putting me down and telling me I won’t make it and to stop trying. But other days I’m running 5km + without even trying and my mind is in a great zone as if there’s a drill sergeant up my ass.

​

It could be that I’m tired, but not noticeably, as I’ve felt the same during two particular workouts one week and one of those workouts I stopped at 1.3km and the other I stopped at 5.8km. And if I’m being honest, my workout was harder and I was more sore during the workout where I ran the greater distance.

​

Anyone have any answers, or experienced something similar? I know it’s not a lot to go on and may not make any sense, but any input is appreciated, thanks guys.

​

edit: and when I say I stopped at 1.3km I meant my whole body felt like shutting down and my mind just wouldn’t stop racing with deconstructive and de-motivational (is that a word?) thoughts, similar to hitting the wall.

summary: How should I increase my speed for rugby? via /r/Fitness
title: How should I increase my speed for rugby? via /r/Fitness
body:
I am a 16/m who just got into rugby and I love it. Problem is I’m kind of slow. What’s the best way to increase my speed? I don’t know if I should run long distances or sprints or both. Also I have found it that if I do run it has to be before I lift since I don’t get home from school until 3:30ish and by the time I’m done lifting ( I run nSuns 5d) it’s already dark. Does this have any different affect as opposed to running after lifting?
